title: For Sale:  Stevens 520 Takedown 12ga
postcontent: Great condition Stevens 520, with the early double hump receiver. Date of manufacturer is hard to pin down on these, but the double hump receiver was at least mid-1930s or before, and the inertial slide release design and company name/location means its a 1909-1913 model. This gun has been reblued a number of years back, and has a nice deep blue finish on it. There are normal wear marks on the magazine tube, and some finish wear is visible on the barrel and grip. The buttstock appears to be either a custom Walnut aftermarket stock, or a factory deluxe model (im not sure which, there are no marking on it that indicate either way), with beautiful deep figure and rich burl on the right-hand side. The buttstock has some minor storage marks on the bottom. The foregrip is the traditional factory ribbed piece, and has a crack running the full length. Because it is a fully captured design, you can see the crack, but it is still solid and wont affect any operation/handling.The gun will slam fire, but it has an inertial lock, meaning unless there is a recoil impulse the gun wont unlock. This was an early safety feature designed for less than reliable ammunition in the hands of people who ran their pump actions too fast (IE, it prevents you from pulling the trigger with the bolt unlocked and a live shell in the chamber, which would cause an out of battery detonation). The system works great and is very reliable. It also has the early "suicide" safety inside the trigger guard, which is kind of like the M1 Garand safety in that you push it forward with your trigger finger to the fire position. The take-down mechanism locks up very tight and is in great mechanical shape.  The gun has a 30" take-down barrel with a traditional bead sight. The magazine holds 5 shells in the tube +1 in the chamber. Chamber is the standard 2 3/4". Bore is not perfect, but pretty darn close!I can provide more detailed pictures of anything that you want to take a closer look at.FTF in Warner Robins GA, or will ship to your FFL for cost with payment via postal money order.

title: For Sale:  Arsenal SAM7K AK-47 Pistol!!!
postcontent: Hi there, I am finally yet regretfully selling the AK pistol that you've always wanted, yet you could never just man up and buy. As said in the title, this is an ARSENAL AK-47 Pistol. What does that mean you ask? it means that it is the most prestigeous and most highly crafted manufacturer compared to any other manufacturer of AK-variant Firearms. A brief background in Arsenal and AK-47 pistols/rifles for those that are new to this type of firearm:- Arsenal is manufactured in Bulgaria and assembled in Las Vegas, NV; Bulgaria being one of several different countries that manufacture/restore AK-variant firearms such as Romania, Russia, China, Israel, and Egypt to name a few others.- The AK-47 uses a gas piston system which is known as being one of the most reliable systems for delivery known to have ever been created. I like to reference it as the Glock of the Rifle world. You can literally throw it in nearly anything mother nature can abuse it with, except for maybe lava, and it will still function and perform very well. - The difference between an AK-47 pistol and AK-47 rifle is that the pistols come with no stock, but with usually shorter barrels on them and are usually intended for its compactness or for the purpose to convert it into a short-barreled rifle (SBR).- AK-47 firearms shoot 7.62x39 ammunition. it is a 30 caliber round that is very effective for a various different scope of uses. Alongside that, the ammo is some of the very cheapest prices in terms of cost that pale in comparison to most other rounds, even compared to the highly popular 5.56x45(AR-15) ammo. (example: 5.56x45 @ 20 rounds =8-10 USD/7.62x39@50 rounds for 11 USD)Now, to compare my Arsenal SAM7K with the original AK-47 platform. - To start, most AK-47 firearms produced were manufactured using stamping of the receivers. To sort of explain, it is a sheet of metal (bar stock) that is literally stamped using a die into the shape of the reciever. - Whereas my reciever, a milled reciever, is a block of steel that is carved out and forged, including the internals, to the shape of the reciever.  - The milled reciever is the most realiable, most accurate-shooting and most functionable method for creating recievers. That is why it comes with a higher price tag as well, but well worth the money.- The SAM7K adopted some other features from another firearm, the famoust Zastava M92 Krink Pistol. Some differences are as listed: The grip is larger, it comes with secondary safety selector integrated into the grip (which is very convenient for users, especially right handers), it comes with 2 positions for the rear sight (peep hole and Notch), and a larger bolt lever; All of which I believe really updated the soviet-era firearm to the standards of todays more modern firearms. - Normally AK-47's come with wood or synthetic wood furniture, but the SAM7K comes with a very high grade polymer, which I personally prefer and gives it a very tactical look, with an ease of maintaining. - Most AK-47's that are sold today are more often than not never fully new production. You either see refurbished firearms or a mixture between new and used parts. However, the SAM7K is 100% new-production of parts and components. It comes with a Cold hammer-forged barrel, unlike many others, which is the highest quality barrel. Also comes with a hard-chrome plated bore and chamber, and also comes with an AK scope rail integrated into the reciever for ultimate ease of mounting/unmounting scope. Thes differences are what set apart Arsenal Inc. Firearms compared to any other manufacture that dares to compete against them. Furthermore, the SAM7K is that much more modernized and functionable compared to any other AK-variant. What it comes with:- SAM7K Pistol (I have not put more than ~ 700 rounds through it and regularly maintained and cleaned) $1350- the pistol originally comes with a barrel shroud, a.k.a an impersonating muzzle break/flash hider with 0% functionality other than looks. So I took it upon myself to buy an original Bulgarian 4-piece flash hider (the most known and sought after muzzle device for AK firearms). I paid $200 for it. - In order to install the flash hider, I had the barrel shortened ~2 inches, crowned and threaded. $50- I also had the feed ramp, trigger, and bolt rails polished to have an action as smooth as glass, if not smoother. $60- it comes with 3 Magpul MOE P-mag 30 rounders. $20 a piece.- and last it comes with a single-point sling for ease and support of shooting. $50.* total value approximately $1750To wrap things up, this SAM7K is the firearm you want and need to have in your collection if you are in the market of AK-47's. you will not regret it your lifelong investment. Also, due to the rising demand of firearms in the middle east, Arsenal has announced that it will pause production of their weapons in the U.S. indefinately to keep up with their high demand of products. That means value is going up, and so is prestige and availability. Last note, please only serious inquiries. Also, the transfer fees will be due to the buyer of the firearm.Thank you, Emmanuel
